@da-woods you are right :-/. I missed that. What I see as a pain in pure python mode is that it does not raise error that `Py_ssize_t` is not declared but it just fallbacks to object instead :-/. I expect that it should behave like regular python [1]:
```python
$ python
Python 3.9.12 (main, May  8 2022, 18:05:13)
[Clang 12.0.0 (clang-1200.0.32.29)] on darwin
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
>>> aa: Spam
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
NameError: name 'Spam' is not defined
```


Btw. it is funny that `declare()` is fine with just `Py_ssize_t` - here is part of generated c file:
```
/* "matrix_with_buffer.py":7
 * 
 * @cython.cclass
 * class Matrix:             # <<<<<<<<<<<<<<
 *     ncols: cython.Py_ssize_t
 *     shape = cython.declare(Py_ssize_t[2])
 */
struct __pyx_obj_18matrix_with_buffer_Matrix {
  PyObject_HEAD
  Py_ssize_t ncols;
  Py_ssize_t shape[2];
  Py_ssize_t strides[2];
  std::vector<float>  v;
};
```

[1] Yes, I know that in future python (PEP 563) is not not evaluating annotations during runtime, but I still think that cython should raise an error because we do evaluate annotations during compilation.
